### Education

The [Falkland Islands Community School](/Falkland_Islands_Community_School) is the primary educational institution in Stanley. Prior to that, the Stanley Infant & Junior School, located at the intersection of John Street and Villiers Street, opened its doors in 1955 and currently educates approximately 250 students aged four to eleven. The Falkland Island Community School (FICS), situated on Reservoir Road, caters to around 220 students between the ages of 11 and 16. For post-secondary education, sixth-form students attend [Peter Symonds College](/Peter_Symonds_College) in England, while those pursuing national diploma or NVQ qualifications enroll at [Chichester College](/Chichester_College), also in England.

### Economy

Today, the government is a significant employer in Stanley, with roughly one-third of the city's residents on its payroll. Tourism also plays a crucial role, particularly on days when two or more large cruise ships grace the town's harbour, often leading to a temporary surge where tourists outnumber the local population.

Historically, [peat](/Peat) was a vital source of heating and fuel in Stanley. While its prominence has waned, stacks of drying peat, carefully covered, can still be observed near some residences, a visual echo of a bygone era.

### Nearby points of interest

A short distance from Stanley lies [Gypsy Cove](/Gypsy_Cove), a popular spot for observing [Magellanic penguins](/Magellanic_penguin). Also nearby is [Cape Pembroke](/Cape_Pembroke), the easternmost extremity of the Falkland Islands. Gypsy Cove, located four miles (6 km) from Stanley, is accessible by taxi or on foot.

### Notable people associated with Stanley

*   See also: [Bishop of the Falkland Islands](/Bishop_of_the_Falkland_Islands), [Governor of the Falkland Islands](/Governor_of_the_Falkland_Islands), and [Chief Executive of the Falkland Islands](/Chief_Executive_of_the_Falkland_Islands)

*   **George Rennie** (1801 or 1802 – 1860), a sculptor, politician, and governor, born in Phantassie, East Lothian, and died in London.

*   **Mary Ellaline Terriss, Lady Hicks** (1871 – 1971), known professionally as Ellaline Terriss, was a celebrated English actress and singer, born in Stanley. She gained widespread acclaim for her performances in Edwardian musical comedies and lived to the remarkable age of 100.

*   **Edward Binnie** (1884 – 1956), born in Stanley, served as the second resident magistrate of South Georgia from October 1914 to April 1927. Prior to this, he held the position of customs officer on East Falkland Island. He passed away in Sandefjord, Norway.

*   **McDonald Hobley** (1917 – 1987), born in Stanley, was among the inaugural continuity announcers for [BBC Television](/BBC_Television), a role he held from 1946 to 1956.

*   **Sir Rex Hunt** CMG (1926 – 2012), born in Redcar, served as the [Governor](/Governor_of_the_Falkland_Islands) during the tumultuous period of the [Falklands War](/Falklands_War). He died in Stockton on Tees.

*   **Gerald Reive** (born 1937), born in the Falkland Islands, is a New Zealand-based athlete who competed as a lawn bowler at the [2010 Commonwealth Games](/2010_Commonwealth_Games).

*   **Terry Peck** MBE, CPM (1938 – 2006), born and died in Stanley, was a distinguished soldier, policeman, and legislator.

*   **Edward Neill "Ted" Baker** CNZM (born 1942), born in Stanley, is a prominent New Zealand scientist specializing in protein purification, crystallization, and bioinformatics.

*   **Alejandro Betts** (1947 – 2020), born in the Falklands, was an Argentine air-traffic controller. He is notable for being the only Falkland Islander to publicly support Argentina's claim to the Falkland Islands.

*   **Mensun Bound** (born 1953), born in Port Stanley, is a British marine archaeologist based in Oxford. He holds the position of Triton Senior Research Fellow in Marine Archaeology at Oxford University.

*   **James Peck** (born 1968), born in Stanley, is an artist and writer. He once held both Argentine and British citizenship but has since renounced his Argentine citizenship.

#### Modern-day politicians

*   **Janet Lynda Cheek** (born 1948), born in Stanley, is a politician who served as a [MLA](/Legislative_Assembly_of_the_Falkland_Islands) for the Stanley constituency from 1997 to 2005 and again from 2009 to 2017.

*   **Mike Summers** OBE (born 1952), born in Stanley, is a politician who served as a [MLA](/Legislative_Assembly_of_the_Falkland_Islands) for the Stanley constituency from 2011 to 2017.

*   **Sharon Halford** (born 1953), born in Stanley, is a politician who served as a [MLA](/Legislative_Assembly_of_the_Falkland_Islands) for the Camp constituency from 1993 to 2001 and again from 2009 until 2013.

*   **Glenn Ross** (born 1964), born in Stanley, is an engineer and politician who served as a [MLA](/Legislative_Assembly_of_the_Falkland_Islands) for the Stanley constituency from 2009 to 2011.

*   **Michael Poole** (born 1984), born in the Falkland Islands, is a politician who served as a [MLA](/Legislative_Assembly_of_the_Falkland_Islands) for the Stanley constituency from 2013 to 2017.

*   **Gavin Short** (born 1962), born in the Falkland Islands, is a politician and served as a [MLA](/Legislative_Assembly_of_the_Falkland_Islands) for the Stanley constituency between 2009 and 2017. He is currently a senior news reporter with [FIRS](/Falkland_Islands_Radio_Service) and was re-elected in the 2021 elections.

### Twin towns

Stanley shares a special bond with two towns in the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom): [Whitby](/Whitby) in [North Yorkshire](/North_Yorkshire), and [Airdrie](/Airdrie,_North_Lanarkshire) in [North Lanarkshire](/North_Lanarkshire).